# Release Notes: V1.3.0 🚀
We are excited to announce the release of Folding v1.3.0 to the main branch! This update marks a significant step toward the implementation of a global job store.

## Highlights ✨
### Global Job Store Framework 🏗️
A foundational implementation for uploading jobs to an rqlite database has been introduced, secured via the Epistula protocol.
This is currently only there as a proof of concept, it won't be used for any of the functionality at the moment. We will monitor if jobs are being sent successfully, the code for the API can be found here: https://github.com/macrocosm-os/golgi-apparatus.

Epistula enhances security and efficiency in job handling. For more details on getting started with Epistula, visit the epistula documentation: https://epistula.sybil.com/. We have an implementation of epsitula in Atom which can be found here: https://github.com/macrocosm-os/atom. This repository serves as a SDK supporting Bittensor subnets.

## Fix to Main 
Hey everyone -- we have looked into the issue of the inactive hotkeys stealing incentive from the network and have concluded that this is because miners can use our `PingSynapse` as an attack vector. 

Right now, miners must explicitly accept a job to be considered to be in the batch of uids for that protein. However, if you have high incentive, you can turn off your miner and always deny doing work. Therefore, you are then subjected to all other miners to try and do better than you overtime. 

With the push to main, we remove the `PingSynapse` entirely, and *all* miners are now randomly sampled. Furthermore, we remove the ability for miners to eject themselves form jobs, removing the use of the `miner_serving` flag to drop uids during the job. This is also to avoid this unwanted behaviour of miners doing nothing and sucking incentive away from honest miners. 

The PR is here: https://github.com/macrocosm-os/folding/pull/298

## The Global Job Pool (GJP) 💾 
Miners have always been subjected to the limitation of what the validator randomly assigns you. This is fine for other subnets where the bandwidth of queries / challenges is high, but this doesn't work for SN25. This is why a subnet like SN9 utilizes HuggingFace. Introducing **The Global Job Pool**. It is a framework that will allow miners to select *any* jobs they want to work on that are inside of the Pool, and submit these to the validators once queried. This *vastly* increases the throughput of the network, and gives complete agency to the miner. Don't want to work on a particular challenge? Fine - Don't! But if you want the most reward, you better get to work. 

If you want to see a basic dashboard of what the Pool currently looks like, we are RIGHT NOW capturing LIVE data from the network. Warning, this is a WIP, and the data is not available via S3 just yet, but it will be *very soon*..... Check it here: https://sn25.api.macrocosmos.ai
